Before analyzing the animal origins of human coronoviruses, it will be useful to examine the definitions and characteristics of evolutionary, natural, reservoir, intermediate and amplifiers of human coronoviruses.
An animal acts as an evolutionary host of a human coronavirus if it hosts a closely related ancestor that shares a high homology at the nucleotide sequence level.
The ancestral virus is usually well adapted and is not pathogen in this guest.
Similarly, a reserve guest houses a human coronavirus in a continuous and long-term manner.
In both cases, the guests are naturally infected and are the natural guests of the human coronavirus or their parental virus.
On the other hand, if the human coronovirus was introduced into the intermediate guest just before or almost at the same time as its introduction into humans, it is not well adapted to the new host and it is usually pathogen.
The intermediate host can act as the zoonotic source of human infection and fulfill the role of host amplifier by allowing the virus to be replicated transiently and then transmitted to humans to amplify the scale of human infection.
A human coronovirus may cause a terminal host infection if it cannot sustain its transmission in the intermediate host.
On the contrary, human coronoviruses can also adapt to the intermediate host and even generate long-term endemicity.
In this case, the intermediate guest becomes a natural reserve guest.
