Handwashing is recommended to prevent the spread of the disease.
The CDC recommends that people wash their hands frequently with water and soap for at least twenty seconds, especially after using the bath or when they have their hands visibly dirty; before eating and after blowing their nose, coughing or sneezing.
This is because, outside the human body, the virus dies when coming into contact with soap, which disintegrates its protective bubble.
The CDC also recommended using an alcohol-based hand disinfectant with at least 60 % of alcohol in volume when water and soap are not available.
WHO recommends that people avoid touching their eyes, nose or mouth without having washed them before.
Surfaces may be decontaminated with several solutions ( within one minute after disinfectant exposure to a stainless steel surface), including ethanol at 62–71 %, isopropanol at 50–100 %, sodium hypochlorite at 0.1 %, hydrogen peroxide at 0.5 % and iodate at 0.2–7.5 %.
Other solutions, such as benzalconium chloride and chlorhexidine gluconate, are less effective.
The CDC recommends that all areas such as offices, bathrooms, common spaces, shared electronic equipment, such as tablets, touchscreens, keyboards, remote controls and ATMs, be disinfected if a case of VOCID is suspected or confirmed in an installation.
Health organizations recommend that people cover their mouth and nose with flexed elbow or a disposable handkerchief for coughing or sneezing, and that they immediately wish the handkerchief.
It is recommended that those who might be infected use surgical masks, as the use of a mask can limit the volume and distance traveled by the air droplets that are dispersed by talking, sneezing and coughing.
WHO issued instructions on when and how to use the masks.
